name: Congressman Bill Keating
tweet_text: We owe it to our country, and we owe it to the thousands of innocent victims, first responders, and fallen heroes who aren‚Äôt here today because of a Tuesday morning that we will never forget. üá∫üá∏

name: Congressman Bill Keating
tweet_text: As we mark this solemn anniversary, I hope that we can all summon the energy to restore that sense of togetherness, patriotism, and common purpose we felt as Americans after September 11 ‚Äì not just today, but every day.

name: Congressman Bill Keating
tweet_text: We have had successes ‚Äì Osama Bin Laden is dead, attempted terrorist attacks have been thwarted, and the world is a safer place with increased international cooperation ‚Äì but those victories serve as no consolation to those who have lost a child, a spouse, a parent, or a friend.

name: Congressman Bill Keating
tweet_text: We will never forget what happened on September 11. We will never forget those who lost their lives and were injured in Afghanistan and Iraq, and we will never forget the sacrifices that their families have made in the ensuing years.

name: Congressman Bill Keating
tweet_text: But we must also remember how we mobilized as a nation and came together as one after September 11, and we must take that memory and move forward to see how we can work together to solve the problems we face both domestically and internationally.

name: Congressman Bill Keating
tweet_text: The twentieth year of U.S. forces coming home with injuries that will impact them and their families for the rest of their lives.

name: Congressman Bill Keating
tweet_text: And, sadly, as we saw just two weeks ago, it is the twentieth year of brave Americans making the ultimate sacrifice for our nation as a result of the War on Terror.

name: Congressman Bill Keating
tweet_text: It‚Äôs also the twentieth year of first responders suffering from medical issues, the result of their courageously rushing through the ash and smoke to Ground Zero to save lives.

name: Congressman Bill Keating
tweet_text: Today also marks the start of the twentieth year of missed birthdays for the children who never had the chance to get to know their parent, the twentieth year of missed wedding anniversaries, the twentieth year of mourning.

name: Congressman Bill Keating
tweet_text: But today is not just the 20th anniversary of a cowardly attack on our nation.

name: Congressman Bill Keating
tweet_text: We remember the horror we felt as we heard the news on that quiet Tuesday morning ‚Äì I was in my car on my way to the office when I heard it on the radio.

name: Congressman Bill Keating
tweet_text: We remember the images of falling towers, a smoldering Pentagon, and the field in Shanksville where courageous passengers and crew died as heroes.

name: Congressman Bill Keating
tweet_text: We remember the more than 6,000 injured.

name: Congressman Bill Keating
tweet_text: We remember the 2,977 innocent lives lost.

name: Congressman Bill Keating
tweet_text: Today we remember.
